title: Grateful Dead Live at Sandstone Ampitheatre on 1990-07-04
lineage: MAC > Tascam 112 analog cassette deck > Edirol UA-5 USB Audio Interface > 24/96 > PC > Audacity (tracks and fades) > Trader's Little Helper > flac 24/96
description:
Set 1

Cold Rain & Snow, Walkin' Blues, Mississippi Half Step, Queen Jane Approximately, Loose Lucy, It's All Over Now, Loser, Promised Land

Set 2

Victim Or The Crime, Foolish Heart, A Little Light, Scarlet Begonias-> Fire On The Mountain, Drums-> Jam-> The Wheel-> Gimme Some Lovin'-> Stella Blue-> Sugar Magnolia, E: U.S. Blues

reviews.review_text: Very good AUD This is one of the better audience recordings that I've heard. Very good quality - thank you for posting. As far as the performance goes, I think that this is a very good show considering that it is 1990. The 2 shows at Sandstone the following year were also good. And you are correct, it was hotter than #%@! that day. I'll never forget it. Thanks for posting.

despite the heat It was a pretty darned good show. There was no shade and it was indeed a scorcher. I recall walking in the asphalt parking lot, and my feet sunk in as if walking on marshmellows - I think that really happened - 

In my memory, Brent was REALLY on in the Scarlet Begonias, he shook the earth and changed the color of the sky. It was tremendous.

Thanks for posting this!

Hot day,hot show and one hot recording!  Yes,it was god awful hot that day. The hottest for the year in Bonner Springs. And Jerry coming out with his freshly cut-off cordaroys and opening with Cold Rain & Snow. Ha-ha,very funny Jerry! Anyway,the show was a good tour opening night. Loose Lucy was such fun that night! And the Loser was pretty spot on. The real magic came in the 2nd set. Victim>Foolish was done well. My favorite Just A Little Light then the Scarlet>Fire. MIDI style heaven at points during the transition jam and in the jams during Fire. The back half of the set is just as strong with a really sweet Stella Blue and the Sugar Magnolia rocks out pretty darn hard. This would be the last time I saw Brent live and I'll take it. Brent was on this night and when we heard about his passing,I just knew that this was going to be really bad in the long run.
 What I'd love to know is where exactly this was recorded at Sandstone. It's so punchy sounding and just "right there". We were in about the 20th row in that first section and this recording is like being there in the 'pit' as it were.
